'''Hollis Robbins''' (born 1963) is an American academic and scholar in the humanities, specializing in literature and poetry.[[File:Hollis_Robbins.jpg|thumb]] ==Career== Hollis Robbins is [https://web.sonoma.edu/ah/about-dean.html Dean of the School of Arts & Humanities] at [[Sonoma State University]] in Rohnert Park, California. Previously, she was Chair of the Department of Humanities at the [[Peabody Institute]]<ref> Faculty Bio http://peabody.jhu.edu/faculty/hollis-robbins/</ref> of the [[Johns Hopkins University]] as well as the Director of the Center for Africana Studies at Johns Hopkins, from 2014-2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://krieger.jhu.edu/africana/2017/04/03/congratulations-to-our-own-hollis-robbins/|title=Hollis Robbins|publisher=|accessdate=2 May 2016}}</ref> Robbins is a noted expert in the field of [https://hub.jhu.edu/magazine/2017/winter/hollis-robbins-nineteenth-century-women-interview/ nineteenth-century African American literature]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hub.jhu.edu/magazine/2017/winter/hollis-robbins-nineteenth-century-women-interview/ |title=Hopkins Magazine interview|publisher=|accessdate=2 April 2018}}</ref> and recently co-edited with [[Henry Louis Gates, Jr.]] an [http://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/books/302222/the-portable-nineteenth-century-african-american-women-writers-by-various/9780143105992/ anthology] of African American women's writing. Robbins' work focuses primarily on nineteenth and early twentieth century black print culture;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nationalhumanitiescenter.org/meet-the-fellows/hollis-robbins/|title=Hollis Robbins at NHC|publisher=|accessdate=2 April 2018}}</ref> she is affiliated with the [http://blackpressresearchcollective.org/visualizing-the-history-of-the-black-press-in-the-united-states-workshop-at-the-center-for-africana-studies-at-johns-hopkins-university/ Black Press Research Collective] and serves as an advisor to the Black Periodical Literature Project at the [[W.E.B. Du Bois Institute]] at [[Harvard University]]. Robbins has been the winner of numerous awards and fellowship including the 2014 Johns Hopkins University Alumni Excellence in Teaching Award,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://peabodyinstitute.wordpress.com/2014/04/02/hollis-robbins-will-receive-jhu-alumni-association-excellence-in-teaching-award/|title=Hollis Robbins will receive JHU Alumni Association Excellence in Teaching Award|work=The Peabody Post|accessdate=2 May 2016}}</ref> a 2015 Johns Hopkins University [https://research.jhu.edu/major-initiatives/discovery-awards/2015-awardees/ Discovery Award], and a fellowship from the [[National Humanities Center]].<ref>http://nationalhumanitiescenter.org/nhc-names-fellows-2017-18/</ref>
Robbins received a B.A. from the [[Johns Hopkins University]], a Masters in Public Policy from Harvard's [[Kennedy School of Government]] in 1990, an M.A. in English literature from the [[University of Colorado, Boulder]], and a Ph.D. from [[Princeton University]] in 2003. Robbins serves on the Faculty Editorial Board of the [[Johns Hopkins University Press]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.press.jhu.edu/about/faculty_board.html|title=The Johns Hopkins University Press - JHU Press Faculty Editorial Board|publisher=|accessdate=2 May 2016}}</ref> From 2004-2006 Robbins was an Assistant Professor of English at [[Millsaps College]] in Jackson, Mississippi.
Previously, Robbins edited several other books with [[Henry Louis Gates, Jr.]], including ''The Annotated Uncle Tom's Cabin'' (2006) and ''In Search of Hannah Crafts: Essays on The Bondwoman's Narrative'' (2003).<ref name="OUP">{{cite web |url=http://www.oup.com/us/catalog/general/subject/HistoryAmerican/AfricanAmerican/?view=usa&ci=9780195309638 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-05-22 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522144800/http://www.oup.com/us/catalog/general/subject/HistoryAmerican/AfricanAmerican/?view=usa&ci=9780195309638 |archivedate=2011-05-22 |df= }}</ref><ref>http://www.perseusbooksgroup.com/civitas/book_detail.jsp?isbn=0465027083</ref> She also co-edited ''The Works of William Wells Brown'' (2006) with [https://www.warren-wilson.edu/academics/academic-affairs/vpaa Paula Garrett] <ref name="OUP" /> and an edition of Frances E.W. Harper's 1892 novel [[Iola Leroy]].<ref> Iola Leroy https://www.amazon.com/Leroy-Frances-Ellen-Watkins-Harper/dp/014310604X</ref>
Robbins writes and publishes on African American [http://blog.bestamericanpoetry.com/the_best_american_poetry/2014/05/the-caged-bird-sings-by-hollis-robbins.html poets] and on film music.<ref>"U.S. History in 70 MM." [review of Quentin Tarantino's [[The Hateful Eight]]] ''The Journal of the Gilded Age and Progressive Era''. 15 (3): 368–370. July 2016.</ref> Her own poetry has been published in ''[[The Cortland Review]],'' ''[[Mezzo Cammin]],'' ''Per Contra'', ''Boston Literary Magazine'' and other literary journals, and has been set to music by [[Peabody Institute|Peabody]] composers.<ref>http://www.peabody.jhu.edu/past_issues/spring10/finding_their_voice.html</ref>
