[[File:Stanley Leighton.jpg|right|thumb|200px|Leighton in 1895.]]
'''Stanley Leighton''' (1837 &ndash; 4 May 1901) was an English barrister, landowner, artist and [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] politician. He is also known as an antiquarian and author.

==Life==
Leighton was the younger son of [[Sir Baldwin Leighton, 7th Baronet]], of Loton Park, and his wife Mary Parker. He was educated at [[Harrow School]] and [[Balliol College, Oxford]]. He then attended [[Inner Temple]] and was [[Call to the bar|called to the bar]] on 18 November 1861, proceeding to the [[Oxford Circuit]]. In 1867 he travelled to the colonies with his friend and fellow-barrister, Rees Davies. His diaries record a trip to India and Ceylon in 1867-1868 and the pair visited Australia in 1868 where Leighton produced many original sketches.<ref>[http://www.nla.gov.au/pub/nlanews/2008/jun08/story-1.pdf Judging progress towards a civilised society - Stanley Leighton’s colonial Australian tour, 1868]</ref> In 1869 his father passed on to him the Sweeney estate at [[Oswestry]] which had come to his mother through the Parker family. He became [[Justice of the Peace|J.P.]] for Shropshire in 1869 and also [[Deputy Lieutenant]]. He was also a Captain of the 15th Shropshire Rifle Volunteers which he remained until 1888<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=1n8BP7HsKCwC&pg=PA177 William Retlaw Williams ''The Parliamentary History of the County of Worcester''  2008]</ref>

Leighton owned brickworks at Sweeney, near Oswestry, which he leased to the Oswestry Coal & Brick Co. Ltd. before 1880, then to the Sweeney Brick Co. Ltd., and after 1885 it was leased to Kay & Hindle Ltd. as the Sweeney Brick & Terra-cotta Works.<ref>[http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/A2A/records.aspx?cat=166-mi5715&cid=-1&Gsm=2008-06-18#-1 Shropshire Archives]</ref> In 1875, he purchased Llwyd's Mansion, an impressive timber framed building in the centre of Oswestry dating from 1604, which was then renovated and divided into shops.<ref>[http://www.discovershropshire.org.uk/html/search/verb/GetRecord/theme:20070306151620 Discovering Shropshire's History - Oswestry Town Trail]</ref>

In 1874 Leighton stood unsuccessfully for [[Bewdley (UK Parliament constituency)|Bewdley]] but at a by-election in 1876 he was elected [[Member of Parliament]] for [[North Shropshire (UK Parliament constituency)|North Shropshire]] and held the seat until it was reorganised in 1885. He was then elected for [[Oswestry (UK Parliament constituency)|Oswestry]] and held the seat until his death.

Leighton was an antiquary and active member of the [[Society for the Protection of Ancient Buildings]]<ref>[http://www.marxists.org/archive/morris/works/1880/spab4.htm Annual Report of The SPAB - III By William Morris]</ref>  which was founded by [[William Morris]] and [[Philip Webb]] in 1877, to oppose what they saw as the insensitive renovation of ancient buildings then occurring in [[Victorian architecture|Victorian]] [[England]]. In 1888 he was Honorary Commissioner for [[South Australia]] at the Paris Exhibition 1888, and he was author of ''Records of Oswestry''. His ''Shropshire houses: past & present; illustrated from drawings (1901)'' was complete and in the printer's hands at the time of his death.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/shropshirehouses00leiguoft ''Shropshire houses: past & present; illustrated from drawings (1901)'']</ref>

He died of [[pneumonia]] at his London home aged 63, having hastened to vote in the Commons over the Coal Duty Bill.<ref name=schron1>{{cite news|title=The late Mr. Stanley Leighton, M.P., F.S.A.|work=The Shrewsbury Chronicle|date=10 May 1901|page=6}}</ref> He was buried in St Oswald's parish churchyard at Oswestry.<ref name=schron2>{{cite news|title=The Late Mr. Stanley Leighton, The Funeral an Imposing Ceremony|work=The Shrewsbury Chronicle|date=10 May 1901|page=8}}</ref>

Leighton married Jessie Marie Williams-Wynn, daughter of Herbert Bertie Watkin Williams-Wynn on 28 August 1873. Their son [[Bertie Leighton|Bertie Edward Parker Leighton]] (1875–1952) was also MP for Oswestry (1929-1945) and inherited the Sweeney Estate.

